CFH is a Chicago classic. Originally built as a firehouse in 1905, owners Matt and Laura established the original iteration as a go to for fine food and drinks for everyone from neighborhood regulars to visiting celebrities. They then rebuilt after a fire decimated it, coming back even better with an expanded bar area, great menu and 5 star service.

She was knowledgeable with the menu, helped guide us throughout (which we all desperately needed- from drinks, appetizers, entrees and dessert) and we couldn’t have been happier. I would highly recommend requesting her as your server!! Thank you for a great Sunday and all the laughs. We will be back for many more in the future!

Had a great time this weekend at Chicago firehouse. Apps were delicious, started with the firecracker shrimp, crab cake, these little cheese puffs(forgot what they were called) and the Rockefeller oysters. None of these apps were a disappointment. If I had to choose a favorite it would go to the oysters. The second course we got a cup of lobster bisque. Delicious, when ordering lobster bisque there's always a chance that the soup will be either too fishy or too creamy. They are doing it right at the firehouse. Great balance of lobster and cream. The main course we did a good diversity of things.  Pork chop, skirt steak, surf and turf with the delmonico, and two sirloins. Again, nothing was a disappointment. From all the entrees I enjoyed the pork chop the best. The roasted corn under the pork chop was so flavorful. Light and sweet, went well with the chop but i think what won me over was the cooked peach that was on the side. You get two slices of the peach and it was the perfect amount. Desserts were a bit dangerous, I couldn't stop eating any of the desserts.  Apple pie, key lime pie and the chocolate cake. I couldn't stop eating the key lime pie,  i would recommend it. Service was a amazing, Diana took great care of us and would highly recommend requesting her.

I want to start off by saying the food was exceptional and would give 5 stars if I got take out. The service was downright horrendous. Our waiter came to our table asking what we wanted to drink without explaining anything on the menu when I heard him go over the whole thing with the table next to us. He only stopped back two more times to pour wine then take our plates at the end. He brought us dessert menus and put them on the table without saying a word then was shocked when I asked for the check when he returned. He never once asked how our food was or if we needed anything. I said thank you several times and he just would stay silent. We are a younger couple and I hope he wasn’t judging us based on that, but I expect top notch service regardless of how old or young I am.  Let me add to this terrible review. I recently found out the waiter added an additional tip to my check and the only thing the owner of the company did was say I will get a refund. Not even an apology. Nothing. Please be aware of what your check total is because I am sure I’m not the only one they are stealing from.  I will never give this place a dollar again and they are less than a block from my apartment.

I planned a nice dinner to celebrate my engagement to my fiancé, just hours after I popped the question. I picked Firehouse for the reputation for great food and a local spot in the neighborhood (I live just a block away in the South Loop). I had written in my reservation that it was a dinner to celebrate our engagement. Upon arrival, I sneakily whispered to the hostess to be sure they got the communication of our celebration. She whispered back “we’re on it”. My fiancé and I had a good meal, but no mention of the engagement. I was just hoping for maybe a congratulatory dessert or even a verbal acknowledgment. Just anything special to heighten our dining experience. My fiancé and I finished dinner, and I left disappointed. Thankfully, she had no idea that I had tried to plan something special, only to be let down. My fiancé went to the restroom and I quietly asked for the manager when we were leaving. I wanted him to be aware of the situation. He was apologetic, but did not offer any way to rectify to situation. Safe to say, I will not be dining at Firehouse again. Good food and atmosphere, but will now just be a bad memory for me. There are many other restaurants in the city that I know can provide a better dining experience.

I went to a company dinner function and was quite underwhelmed by the food there.  the building itself was very nice and the open floor plan and decor was up to par as well.   However the food was another story.  Our waiter was attentive so service was the best part of the night.  I ordered lobster bisque which had very nice presentation but the taste was bland and no sign of lobster pieces which I am used to.   Appetizer crabcakes was one of 2 better dishes we tried.   I specifically asked the waiter about most of the negative reviews I read on the Yelp were all about the steaks they served.   Since I brought a nice bottle of Sea Smoke Ten Pinot Noir with me, I wanted to have a steak so ordered Kansas City cut which is a bone in New York strip.   I mentioned to waiter to make sure it's medium rare which is important for this cut for me.  I can tolerate medium for ribeye or filet mignon which are more tender to start.  unfortunately mine came in totally pink when I sliced the center of the steak.   they took it back and my second worry came true when the replacement showed very light brown on the surface.  I sliced it and it was almost raw.  Since it was getting late I just accepted it and ate the steak around the area which was too rare even for me.   I have to say the meat itself was quality meat and had nice subtle flavor but the kitchen staff was not very good in controlling the cook time for making steaks.  The best side dish was sauteed mushrooms, not overly heavy on butter or oil or salt like many other places I've been to.  Asparagus was ok, a little too charred for my liking.   I also don't recommend Quilt Cabernet my colleague ordered.  They ended up ordering another Robert Mondavi Cabernet. I can't comment on dessert as I left a little earlier.   If the restaurant can have a better system to manage time steaks spent on the grill or monitor the temperature better it would certainly have at least full 4 star reviews instead of 3.5 which is not very good for an establishment like this.  2 stars for food 4 stars for service.

Very good place to have an awesome dinner. The menu is very well designed. The portions are great. The wine list and scotch lists are small but well thought. Prices are high but fair considering the great quality. Service was phenomenal. Would definitively come back. Here is a dissection of our visit: Reservation at 7 pm: got seated within 2 minutes or less. At the table: water and bread within 2 minutes or less. The menus: there is a kids menu(definitively a plus), the regular menu is very well thought. Appetizers: they had Kumamoto oysters! Grilled octopus.  Among another 6 to 8 choices. Salads: several delightful options. Soups: several delightful options. Main courses: there are options for  fish, chicken, steak, surf and turf, chateaubriand!!!Some plates have option for 2 people. They also have the option for bordelaise sauce on the side. The sides: are awesome and huge portions(the chateaubriand comes with Brussels sprouts or asparagus and potatoes and bordelaise and butter). The wine: good selection and fairly priced. We had the Cava bottle for $32. The scotch: small but very well thought. They have single malts! I ordered a separate glass with ice and a soda water and they didnt charge me separate(I always get irritated when they charge the ice or the soda water at other restaurants). Desserts and coffee: multiple options. The sorbet was very good and a large portion. Our order: 4 people(2 adults, 2 children) Chicken fingers Chicken fingers 6 oysters 1 grilled octopus 1 bottle of cava wine 2 sprites 1 diet coke 1 Chateaubriand 1 Sorbet 1 Higland Park scotch 1 black coffee Total: $250  BONUS: There is point system. Every $300 you get $25 credit.  We will definitively come back!

Ambience is lovely. The building is gorgeous. Great location. Sunday brunch menu was great, unfortunately we were dining around noon so they were sold out of a couple choices. Party of 5. One LOVED his entre, one didn't like theirs, three of us thought our food was good but not great. Eggs atop my Crab Benedict were overcooked so the texture of the dish was off, but the taste was quite delicious. The Baked Eggs dish looked like soup, it had so much bechamel sauce, served with two very dried out pieces of toast, I'm afraid it was a total miss. But the open faced Croque Madame was beautiful to look at and got raves on its taste. I'd go back, and definitely want to try one of their famous steaks for dinner some time.

After a recent very positive dining experience here, I definitely feel the Chicago Firehouse deserves 5 stars.  The ambiance and decor are warm and inviting..  Service was polite, friendly, and impeccable..  and the Food was perfectly prepared and cooked exactly to order.  I had the filet mignon, medium, with bordelaise sauce, sauteed mushrooms (which included a variety of tasty mushrooms) prepared with garlic and onion.  My side dish was whipped garlic mashed potatoes.  Again, perfect flavor combinations.  Yumm. I will Definitely be back, and will tell others to dine there.
